OriginalAxioms:
:CavityOrContainer rdfs:comment The collection of all cavities, containers, and
            hollow  objects. An instance of #$CavityOrContainer
            spatially subsumes a hollow space region, and might include
            as #$physicalParts either no enclosing walls
            #$CavityInteriorRegion, just the inside surface of the
            walls #$CavityWithWalls, or the complete walls
            #$ContainerShapedObject.  #$Containers, such as coffee
            cups, buildings or stomachs, have well-defined outside
            walls.  Instances of #$Cavity such as caves  and rooms do
            not have well-defined outside walls. #$CavityOrContainer
            was reified since certain properties hold true of both
            instances of  #$Container and of #$Cavity, and since we wish
            to use certain  predicates interchangeably. For example, we
            wish to use the same  predicate, #$pipeEndsAtCavity for
            talking about relationships holding  between esophagi and
            stomachs in addition to that which holds between  hallways
            and rooms.

:PoisoningAnOrganism rdfs:comment PoisoningAnOrganism is the intentional 
            delivery of a Poison to some organism, animal or plant, with the
            intenton to kill or harm it.
            
          Includes verb sense 1 of poison in WordNet, but includes
             attempts at poisoning that do not result in death:
            3. 1 poison - kill with poison; She poisoned her husband
          .

:Convoy rdfs:comment This sense is for military land vehicles or a group
        of ships escorted by military vehicles.
        
            COSMO note: a Convoy is interpreted here strictly in
            the military sense.  An analogous grouping of vehicles
            for civilian purposes could be called a Caravan.
            ***ToDo: There is a potential contradiction - if a
            Convoy is strictly a bunch of vehicles, how can it
            be an agent?? The Cyc parent has been removed for review.
            Is it an Organization?

           CYC The collection of all convoys of vehicles.  Each
            instance of #$Convoy is a composite object a #$Group that
            has various #$TransportationDevices as #$groupMembers.  In a
            #$Convoy, the member vehicles travel together in a line and
            close together, one behind the other.  #$Convoys of #$Ships
            and #$Trucks are often used in military operations.
            
            SUMO: A group of people driving vehicles that all have 
            the same destination.  That destination may be an intermediate destination 
            on the way to a final destination for some of the vehicles however.  This 
            is distinguished from vehicles that have no common purpose, such as 
            traffic on a freeway.  This includes cases where some of the agents intend 
            to reach a point but fail to do so.
            
              Includes to parts of noun senses 1 amd 2 of convoy in Wordnet:
                  1. 1 convoy - a procession of land vehicles traveling together
                  2. convoy - a collection of merchant ships with an escort of warships

:detects rdfs:comment This relates a Sensor biological or artifactual to the thing,
           phenomenon. substance, or property that it can detect.  The range is too broad to limit.
           A Sensor can detect light, generally photodetector or patterns of light
           e.g. scenes; or sounds, or motion, or force, or chemical substances, or anything
           else that can be detected.
        
          CYC comment:#$detects SENSOR STUFF means that instance
            SENSOR of #$Sensor has detected STUFF.  Be mindful of the
            difference between #$detects and #$perceives; only
            #$Agents perceive, which is partially accomplished through
            the detection process via some #$Sensors to which they
            are related.  So, for example, you are a perceiver,      but
            your ears or perhaps your auditory sense system as a whole
            are detectors.  Only tangible things, #$PhysicalEvents or
            #$PartiallyTangibles, can be detected

:Aircraft rdfs:comment A self-powered heavier-than-air air transportation 
        device.  Blimps and dirigibles are not included; for lighter-than-air
        devices use  LighterThanAirCraft.  Also, following Cyc, gliders are not
        included in this type.
        
        In cyc called AirTransportationVehicle.
        Cyc: A specialization of #$AirTransportationDevice and
            #$TransportationDevice-Vehicle.  Each instance of
            #$AirTransportationVehicle is a device which is both
            self-powered and controlled in some fashion by a user, and
            is used for transportation through air.  Specializations of
            #$AirTransportationVehicle include the collections
            #$Airplane and #$Ultralight, but not collections of
            non-#$SelfPoweredDevices such as #$Glider.
            
            Corresponds to part of noun sense 1 of aircraft excluding lighter-than-air
             vehicles - use LighterThanAirCraft in WordNet:
               1. 15 aircraft - a vehicle that can fly

:Network rdfs:comment Any Object that is composed of multiple, mostly similar parts that are
          connected to each other by paths physical or metaphorical in such a way that the 
          combination of connections imparts certain properties to the whole that arise from the
          multiple connections and are not present with only one or two connections - though three or four
          pieces or connections can form a primitive Network as in a PictureFrame.
          A SpiderWeb is an instance of Network.

          This is a very general notion, including both physical and abstract
          Objects, such as computer networks, social networks of people, broadcasting networks,
          netting for various purposes, such as fish nets, and frameworks for buildings.
          
          Corresponds to noun sense 1 of network in WordNet:
            1. 23 network, web - an interconnected system of things or people;
              he owned a network of shops; retirement meant dropping out of a 
              whole network of people who had been part of my life; tangled in a web of cloth

:correspondsToDB_Subtable rdfs:comment correspondsToDB_Subtable relates some concept
        in the ontology to a portion of a DatabaseTable,
        consisting of some subset of the records rows, and possibly
        also some subset of the columns.  This relation is used when a
        DatabaseTable is used to represent more than one Type in
        an ontology.  The records that represent the Type must be
        recognizable by the value in some field in the whole DatabaseTable.
        For example, a table that represents the characteristics of both people
        and non-human animals might have a special field labeled BorH,
        which distinguishes humans from Beasts non-human animals, and
        for humans, the value in that field would be H, and for
        Beasts the value would be B.  There might be colums that are not used
        for Beast, and likewise columns not used for Human.  Certain fields
        may be used for both Types, but the meaning of the field may
        differ depending on the type.

:PollingResultType rdfs:comment A PollingResultType a type of attribute
     that measures the result of some poll or other measurement of the
     sentiment of a GroupOfPeople about some issue.  The values are
     expressed as the percentage of the subject Group that answers in 
     a specific way to a specific question.  The values will therefore 
     record the questions asked, the answer, and the fraction of the 
     population giving that answer.

:ModernHumanResidence rdfs:comment The Cyc term for the concept
        Residence in this ontology..

:Behavior rdfs:comment A Behavior is a manner of AnimalActivity that
          has acquired some word to characterize its pattern; it may be performed 
          once or may be repeated at more or less frequent
          intervals, by an individual.  
          
          Behaviors that an individual animal repeats sufficiently often
          that it can be considered a pattern characteristic of the
          animal would be subtypes such as Habit or Practice.
          
          Includes verb sense 1 and 2 of behave and noun senses 1 and 3
                of behavior in WordNet:
            1. 20 act, behave, do - behave in a certain manner; show a 
                certain behavior; conduct or comport oneself; You should act 
                like an adult; Dont behave like a fool; What makes her do this way?;
                The dog acts ferocious, but he is really afraid of people
            2. 4 behave, acquit, bear, deport, conduct, comport, carry -
                behave in a certain manner; She carried herself well; 
                he bore himself with dignity; They conducted themselves well 
                during these difficult times
            WN noun behavior:
              1. 30 behavior, behaviour, conduct, doings - manner of acting
                  or controlling yourself
              3. 8 demeanor, demeanour, behavior, behaviour, conduct, deportment -- 
                 behavioral attributes the way a person behaves toward other people

:Chrysanthemum rdfs:comment A Chrysanthemum is the Flower with or without the stem of a ChrysanthemumPlant.

           Corresponds to noun sense 1 of chrysanthemum in Wordnet:
              1. 1 chrysanthemum - the flower of a chrysanthemum plant

:Fashionable rdfs:comment A QualitativeAttributeValue of Objects or places or Actions that
           conform to the current social fashions or are currently popular.
           This is primarily related to appearance, but
           some aspects of behavior can be included, as in fashionable cafe,
           fashionable resort.  For fashionable as applied to people, use type Stylish.
           The sense of fashionable for places, meaning that the place has
           become popular, is included in this type, but is more specifically
           represented by the subtype FashionablyPopular..
                  
          Corresponds to adjective sense 1 of fashionable and sense 2 of stylish
            and adjective sense 3 of in in WordNet, however the subtypes 
            FashionablyPopular and Stylish distinguish the meanings that relate to objects and to people, 
            respectively.
          WN fashionable
          1. 3 fashionable, stylish - being or in accordance with current social fashions;
            fashionable clothing; the fashionable side of town; a fashionable cafe
          WN in
          3. in - currently fashionable; the in thing to do; large shoulder pads are in

:DosageFormType rdfs:comment Drug products organized according to their form
            when they are given as doses.

:Notoriety rdfs:comment Notoriety is a SocialState a PersistentState of
       BeingRecognized in which the recognition is spread very widely, among
       more than a few people, and the deeds for which a Person is recognized are
       generally considered as bad things.  For wide recognition for doing
       good things, use Fame
    
       Corresponds to noun sense 1 of notoriety in WordNet;
         1. notoriety, ill fame -- the state of being known for some unfavorable act or quality

:appearsToBe rdfs:comment appearsToBe relates a first Object or situation Attribute to
      some second ObjectType, EventType, or instance of Object, where the
      first thing presents a visual appearance of being the second thing.
      This can be used very generally to represent the notion expressed as
      it appears as though or that appears to be.  For the more
      specific case where some PhysicalObject has a close resemblance in
      form to some Object or ObjectType, use resembles.

:OrderedTrio rdfs:comment A OrderedTrio is a Tuple containing three 
      ordered elements.

:Harness rdfs:comment A WearableItem that fits on the torso of a large quadruped such as
          a Horse, Camel, or Ox, that facilitates connection to and use of other items, such
          as a Saddle animal-drawn cart or chariot, or some animal-powered
          device, such as a water wheel or plow.
          
          This is the parent for harnesss that are used on animals and on people -
            see the subtypes Harness-Animal and Harness-Human
          
          CYC: The collection of wearable lattice-shaped
              contraptions that are used to secure some object to the body
              of an #$Animal.

:VisualArtActivity rdfs:comment NOTE that the product need not be FineArt, it can
        be some visual art object that has a practical purpose, such as
        photographs taken for person use or commercial use, as well as
        for the sake of Art.  The thing created may be a physical representation
        other than on a surface, such as a DigitalPhotograph or an image in computer
        memory generated by some computer-based process.
        
        Cyc: The collection of activities that instances of
            #$Artist-Visual do. This includes things like
            #$PaintingAPicture, #$MakingFn #$Sculpture, and #$TakingaPhotograph.

:GeographicalPoint rdfs:comment GeographicalPoint is a merger of the Cyc
           GeographicalPoint-Intangible and #$GeographicalPoint-Intangible-FixedLocation,
           which appeared to make unnecessary distinctions that violate linguistic
           intuitions, be confusing, and possibly redundant.
        
           GeographicalPoint is a location which is a point on the
           surface of the Earth land or water, which will have a measure expressed as
           Latitude and Longitude, and has an altitude of zero relative to the
           standard geoid datum representing the Earths surface.  It is
           therefore located on the geodetic datum.  This differs from Cyc usage.
           The surface used in COSMO is the geoid Datum WSG84.  This is provisional and
           can change.
           
          Cyc - #$GeographicalPoint-Intangible-FixedLocation
            The subcollection of
            #$GeographicalThing-Intangible-FixedLocation whose instances
            are intangible points on the Earths surface that have
            relatively fixed geographic locations.  Each geographical
            point is located on a unique #$LatitudeLine and on a unique
            #$LongitudeLine, and is itself the point of intersection of
            those two lines.
            
          Cyc: GeographicalPoint-Intangible
            The collection of zero dimensional intangible
            geographical  objects [#$GeographicalThing-Intangible.]
            Instances of this collection are typically points on a map.

:CrescentShaped rdfs:comment The property of a two- or three-dimensional  object that
            has a two-dimensional cross-section that is an arc of a
            circle less than one-half the full circle, with some thickness
            to the line that is usually greater toward the middle of the shape.
            This is the shape of the crescent phase of the moon.  Three-dimensional
            Physical objects that are CrescentShaped are usually only very
            approximately shaped like a true crescent, for example a
            Banana or a croissant.
            
            Corresponds to adjective sense 1 and part of noun sense 1 
              not an object that is crescent-shaped  of crescent in WordNet:
              WN noun crescent:
              1. crescent - any shape resembling the curved shape
                 of the moon in its first or last quarters
              WN adj crescent:
                1. crescent, crescent-shaped, semilunar, lunate -
                  resembling the new moon in shape

:Wish rdfs:comment A Wish is a DirectedFeeling in some ways similar to a
      Desire in that it is directed toward some Situation that the agent
      would like to see occur.  However, a Wish can relate to some
      past event, not only to some FutureEvent instance of FutureSituation.
      I wish that she hadnt done
      that.  I is also less likely that a Wish will lead to some Action than
      that a Desire will do so - a Wish can be fairly abstract and weak, not closely
      related to the main interests of an agent: I wish that China would quit
      censoring the internet.
      
      A wish that is expressed explicitly in language is represented as a 
      
      For the sense of wish directed toward a FutureSituation, use Desire.
      
      Corresponds to noun senses 2 and 4 of wish in WordNet:
        2. 2 wish, indirect request - an expression of some desire or inclination; 
           I could tell that it was his wish that the guests leave;
           his crying was an indirect request for attention
        4. wish - the particular preference that you have; it was his last wish; 
        they should respect the wishes of the people

:isaGoalOf rdfs:comment isaGoalOf relates an instance of a Goal to the CognitieAgent
          that has that Goal.  Each instance of a Goal is held by some IntentionalAgent
          animal, person, group for some period of time.  The time interval
          when a Goal is active may be open-ended.

:TelephonePole rdfs:comment A TelephonePole is a Post used to support telephone or
           telegraph wires,   These days it may support other types of wire - e,g cable, 
           
            Corresponds to noun sense 1 of telephone pole in WordNet:
              1. telephone pole, telegraph pole, telegraph post - tall pole supporting telephone wires

:Department rdfs:comment The collection #$Department is a subset of
            #$Organization.  An element of #$Department is a major
            sub-organization of a business, government, or academic
            organization.  An element of #$Department is part of the
            organization to which it belongs, NOT a separate legal
            entity such as a partly or wholly owned subsidiary
            company, and it performs some of the activity of that
            organization.  In Cyc, the collection #$Department includes
            generically what may be called a division, department,
            office, bureau, ministry, etc., within an actual
            organization.  Common types of departments include those
            represented by the subsets #$LegalDepartment,
            #$SecurityDepartment, #$PayrollDepartment,
            #$AccountingDepartment, #$HumanResourcesDepartment,
            #$AcademicDepartment, and CustomerServiceDepartment and
            many others.
            
            Coresponds to sense 1 of department in WordNet:
            1. 28 department, section - a specialized division of a
            large organization; youll find it in the hardware department;
            she got a job in the historical section of the Treasury

:VerbInf rdfs:comment Each instance of
     this category is a verb in the infinitive form.

:Solemnity rdfs:comment Feeling of impressive gravity, as if weighed down
            by deep thought or important work. Not light or frivolous,
            but serious.
            
           Corresponds to noun sense 1 of solemnity in Wordnet:
              2. gravity, solemnity - a solemn and dignified feeling

:wasReplacedBy rdfs:comment wasReplacedBy is the inverse of wasaSubstituteFor.
      This relates some instance of an Entity to an instance of Substitute a Role
      which replaced the subject in some Role
      
      The thing that serves as the Substitute can be of any type of Object.

:Liquid rdfs:comment A quality of objects that can flow freely, like
          water.  This quality depends on temperature; almost all
          substances can be liquiid at some temperature and pressure.
         
         Corresponds to adjective sense 1 of liquid in WordNet:
           1. 25 liquid - existing as or having characteristics of a liquid; 
               especially tending to flow; water and milk and blood are liquid substances

:Brief rdfs:comment Brief is an attribute that specifies that some
        Event lasted in time less than the usual length of time for that
        kind of Event.  This attribute is relative to some norm or expected value.  It has
        no absolute quantitative implication, and is strictly interpreted
        in some context.
               
        Corresponds to adjective sense 1 of short and adjective sense 1 of brief in WordNet:
        1. 43 short - primarily temporal sense; indicating or being or seeming 
            to be limited in duration; a short life; a short flight; a short holiday; 
            a short story; only a few short months
        WN adj brief:
          1. 12 brief, little - of short duration or distance; a brief stay in the country;
            in a little while; its a little way away

:isHigherThan rdfs:comment COSMO note: this relation means that the volumetric
        center of the subject is at a higher altitude in some vertical frame
        than the volumetiric center of the object.
        
        In Cyc called above-Higher:
        Cyc:  #$above-Higher HIGH-OBJ LOW-OBJ means that
            HIGH-OBJ is at a greater altitude from some common
            reference point than LOW-OBJ.  In terrestrial contexts see
            #$TerrestrialFrameOfReferenceMt, #$above-Higher HIGH-OBJ
            LOW-OBJ typically means that HIGH-OBJ-A is at a greater
            altitude above sea level see the predicate
            #$altitudeAboveSeaLevel than LOW-OBJ.

:Setting rdfs:comment A Setting is an Environment-Generic, a Place
           that includes the type of area and the Objects in that Place, providing
           a Context that imparts some properties to the things that occur there
           or induces certain Feelings.

             Corresponds to noun sense 1 of setting in WordNet:
               1. 7 setting, scene - the context and environment in which something is set; 
                 the perfect setting for a ghost story

:Involved rdfs:comment Involved is an AttributeValue of an individual
        thing  that has some relation to some Event.  This is an attribute
        of a Participant in an Event, whose role can usually be directly
        related to the Event itself by some subproperty of hasParticipant.
    
        Corresponds to noun sense 1 of involved in WordNet:
            1. 32 involved - connected by participation or association or use;
              we accomplished nothing, simply because of the large number of
              people involved; the problems involved; the involved muscles; 
              I dont want to get involved; everyone involved in the bribery case
              has been identified

:hadObjectRented rdfs:comment hadObjectRented points from a Renting
         Event to the objects that were rented by the
         act of making the rental agreement.  The objects
         can be concrete or abstract,such as rights.  This is
         for renting anything - cars, apartments, boats, user rights.
         However, financial instruments are not rented.

:Paint rdfs:comment Paint of all kinds, both in its liquid state and
            later in its dried state on a surface.  For the liquid
            paint only, use Paint-undried.  NOTE that this includes as a subtype
            Varnish so a Paint does not necessarily have to have a 
            color, or a pigment as component.
            
            COSMO note: In SUMO Paint is classified as a Solution, but
            paint is physically a Suspension, containing solid undissolved
            pigment particles.  SUMO requires coloring abilty but COSMO does not.
            
         SUMO: Any Solution which is capable of Coloring something.
         
         Corresponds to noun sense 1 of paint in WordNet:
           1. 7 paint - a substance used as a coating to protect or 
             decorate a surface especially a mixture of pigment suspended 
             in a liquid; dries to form a hard coating

:ClipperShip rdfs:comment A fast SailingShip.  
        
           Corresponds to noun sense 1 of clipper ship in Wordnet:
              1. clipper, clipper ship - a fast sailing ship used in former times

:Strike rdfs:comment A Strike is an intentional refraining from performing some
          paid labor that had been performed.  This is a PersistentState that
          is caused by and immediately follows a GoingOnStrike Event.
          
          @ToDo: NOTE that as of rev885, only a LaborUnion can be designated as
           the Agent performing the Strike.  In general in a ConflictEvent
           wasPerformedByAgent points to all parties of a conflict.
           In this case the restriction only points to one party, but since
           that party is an Organization, the plurality of the object of
           the relation is preserved, and there is no logical inconsistency.
           But whether both parties need to perform a conflict needs to 
           be reconsidered.
          
            Corresponds to noun sense 1 and verb sense 7 of strike in WordNet: 
              1. 441 strike, work stoppage - a groups refusal to work 
                in protest against low pay or bad work conditions;
                the strike lasted more than a month before it was settled
             WN verb strike:
                7. 3 strike, walk out - stop work in order to press demands;
                The auto workers are striking for higher wages;
                The employees walked out when their demand for better benefits was not met

:Merriment rdfs:comment Merriment is  the emotion experienced when one finds something
            very enjoyable or amusing, to the point where they smile or laugh.  This is a
            higher level of good feeling than just having a good time.
            This  usually occurs for intervals of time that are more than
            just momentary.
            
            Corresponds to noun sense 1 of merriment and sense 1 of gaiety in Wordnet:
            WN merriment
            1. 2 gaiety, merriment - a gay feeling

:Jewish rdfs:comment Jewish is a PertainingAttributeValue that pertains to
    JewishPerson or the Jews or Judaism or he culture of the Jews.
     This is usually written with a capital J.
    
         Corresponds to noun sense 1 of Jewish in WordNet:
           1. 52 Jewish, Judaic - of or relating to Jews or their culture or religion;
             He is Jewish; a Jewish wedding

:FamilyLine rdfs:comment A FamilyLine is a KinshipGroup, related by birth and
            mating, broader and more inclusive than Family-Human, approximately
            the same as the technical term Sib.
            
              Corresponds to noun sense 1 of family line in WordNet:
                1. family, family line, folk, kinfolk, kinsfolk, sept, phratry - 
                  people descended from a common ancestor; his family has lived in 
                  Massachusetts since the Mayflower

:wasaTransporterInEvent rdfs:comment wasaTransporterInEvent points from a TransportationDevice
      to some TransportationEvent in which the transporter was used.
      A TransportationDevice can be the transporter in many
      TransportationEvents.

:Computer rdfs:comment COSMO: This is for electronic digital computers.
        
        Cyc: A specialization of #$ComputationalSystem,
            #$ElectronicDevice, and #$ComputerHardwareItem.  Each
            instance of #$Computer is an electronic device that acts on
            input according to some set of instructions often in the
            form of software - see #$ComputerProgram-CW producing some
            output.  Instances of #$Computer have specialized parts to
            handle input and output sometimes peripherals like screens
            and keyboards, sometimes just input-output terminals on a
            chip, storage internal memory and external storage such as
            disk drives, and reasoning see #$CentralProcessingUnit.
            The more specialized collection #$PersonalComputer is the
            collection of the popular archetypes of what a computer is
            e.g., desktop, laptop, and palm computers; however,
            instances of #$Computer are incorporated into many devices
            e.g., cars, cameras, and VCRs.  Hydraulic computers,
            analog computers, biological computers, etc. are not
            instances of this collection because #$Computer is a
            specialization of #$ElectronicDevice.
            
            Corresponds to noun sense 1 of computer in WordNet:
            1. 6 computer, computing machine, computing device, data processor,
              electronic computer, information processing system - 
              a machine for performing calculations automatically

:Sorry rdfs:comment COSMO note: this is the attribute of someone
         experiencing Sorrow.
         
            
            Corresponds to adjective senses 1 and 2 of sorry in WordNet:
              1. 3 pitying, sorry - - feeling or expressing sorrow or pity;
                 a pitying observer threw his coat around her shoulder
              2. 1 regretful, sorry, bad - - feeling or expressing regret 
                  or sorrow or a sense of loss over something done or undone; 
                  felt regretful over his vanished youth; regretful
                  over mistakes she had made; he felt bad about breaking the vase

:Jerk rdfs:comment A Jerk is a vague term for a Person with one or more characteristics
           that are considered socially undesirable, the most prominent one being that
           that person is Stupid in some way - perhaps just socially, but perhaps in other ways as
           well.  The WN suggests also fatuous silly, and RHW sugests naive.
           
           COSMO requires srupid and silly - the other characteristics
             are optional.
                
             RHW: jerk 4: Slang. a contemptibly naive, fatuous, foolish, or inconsequential person.
                
              Corresponds to noun sense 1 of jerk in Wordnet:
                 1. 2 jerk, dork - a dull stupid fatuous person

:Rug rdfs:comment From plush room-sized Oriental rugs to
            rubber-backed bathroom rugs, this collection represents
            textile floor coverings that are not attached.
            The restriction that it cannot be attached distingjuishes a 
            Carpet which may or may not be attached from a Rug in COSMO.
            
            SUMO: A piece of Fabric whose purpose is to cover a Floor.
            
            Corresponds to part rug of noun sense 1 of rug in WordNet.
            1. 4 rug, carpet, carpeting - floor covering consisting 
              of a piece of thick heavy fabric usually with nap or pile

:Restraint rdfs:comment Restraint  is a form of *negative* Capability, i.e. it is
          an *inability* to do something. For restrictions on movement, 
          use RegionLimitation.
          
          
          There are three parts to a Restraint
           1.  The Rule or Condition that restrains the agent from doing
                 something.  A Restraint is an externally imposed Limitation,
                 such as a rule as  a law, parental rule, law of nature,
                 or even a moral inhibition.
           2.  The type of restraint: legal, physical, moral, social
           3.  The Action which one is restrained from performing.
        
        Corresponds only approximately to noun sense 3 of restraint in WordNet:
          WN restraint:
            3. constraint, restraint - the state of being physically constrained; 
              dogs should be kept under restraint

:_WhenFn_Physical_ rdfs:comment A UnaryFunction that maps an Object or Process to 
      the exact TimeInterval during which it exists.  Note that, for every TimePoint
      ?TIME outside of the TimeInterval WhenFn ?THING, time ?THING ?TIME does not hold.

:PumpkinPlant rdfs:comment An individual pumpkin.
        
         Corresponds to sense 1 of pumpkin and sense 1 of pumpkin vine in WordNet:
           1. pumpkin, pumpkin vine, autumn pumpkin, Cucurbita pepo -
              a coarse vine widely cultivated for its large pulpy round orange fruit 
              with firm orange skin and numerous seeds; subspecies of Cucurbita pepo include the
              summer squashes and a few autumn squashes

:AbilityToDoArithmetic rdfs:comment The ability to add, subtract, multiply,
          or divide numbers.  This covers the full range of arithmetic
          ability from simple addition to root extraction.
          
          See AddingEvent, DoingAddition.

:InstantaneousEvent rdfs:comment called Event in ISO15926
     COSMO note:  An InstantaneousEvent is a change that occurs instantaneously -
        the change can be said to occur at one point in time: a system has a set
        of attributes that are effective at that point in time, and at any point 
        prior to that, the state may be different in one or more ways. 
        For physical events, this is unrealistic but can be a useful abstraction.
        Certain social or mental events can be said to be instantaneous, such as
        a change in title or position that is scheduled ahead of time.

        In ISO15926 and some situation calculus representations, processes 
        are simply a series of instantaneous changes followed by periods State of no change.
        So this is an important concept for some process representations.

:Rip rdfs:comment Each Rip is a Defect in Sheetlike SolidObject
           consisting of a visible line of separation of what were adjacent parts of
           a SheetOfSomeStuff usually cloth or paper.
           In COSMO this is a PhysicalObject consisting of the separation plus the 
             adjacent parts that make it clear enable one torecognize 
             that it is a separation of some sheet.
           
           This would not be used to apply to situations where a SheetOfSomeStuff
                were separated completely into two or more parts.

            ARip in a stocking would be the subtype Ravel  a run.

:UnaryFunction rdfs:comment The Class of Functions that require a single argument.

:PhysicalFilter rdfs:comment COSMO note: Filters are not necessarily  Networks,
           since matted fibers are not physically connected to each other
           by links, but are retained in shape by topological constraints.
           But a Net is a Network as well as a PhysicalFilter.
           Being a PhysicalFilter means that it is a form of barrier that
           is only non-permeable to solid objects greater than a certain variable size.
        
           Cyc: #$PhysicalFilter is a specialization of
            #$NonPoweredDevice.  Each instance of #$PhysicalFilter is a
            simple physical filter device, which allows some
            materials/objects to pass through, while preventing others
            from doing so.  Some notable specializations are
            #$CoffeeFilter and #$WindowScreen.  Natural filters do not
            fall within this collection.
            
            COSMO note: this generic concept of Filter includes
            things not always called filters, such as 
            screens used for filtering solid mixtures.  For the
            more common liquid and gas filters, use Filter.

:SouthernDrawl rdfs:comment The distinctive Pronunciation of English that is used by
        native English speakers raised in some southeastern parts of the United States,
        expsecially in Georgia, Alabama, and Mississippi, and in some neighboring
        regions.  The accents vary but can all be recognized as southern by
        native English speakers of northern and western USA..

:ImmersingSomethingInaLiquid rdfs:comment To intentionally immerse an object liquid, whether or not it is subsequently withdrawn.
           This must occur in a gravitational field, therefore an immersion is necessarily
           a Lowering.  However not every Lowering is caused by an IntentionalAgent, therefore this
           is also a subtype of DirectedTranslation.

           The restriction requires specifying  some Liquid type of LiquidObject when
              referring to an instance of immersing.  See subtype SubmergingInWater.
            
           The closest WN sense of immerse is sense 1:
           1. 3 immerse, plunge - thrust or throw into; Immerse yourself in hot water
              The gloss does not seem to include a controlled immersion, but dip see DippingSomething 
           is a subtype in WN, so this must include the intended sense.
:HistoricalAccount rdfs:comment The SUMO term for HistoricalNarrative.

:French rdfs:comment French is a PertainingAttributeValue that pertains to
    France.  This is usually written with a capital F.
    
          Corresponds to noun sense 1 of French in WordNet:
            1. 11 French, Gallic - of or pertaining to France or the people of France; 
            French cooking; a Gallic shrug

:KosherFood rdfs:comment The collection of all food that may be eaten
            according to the #$KosherCodeOfConduct.  This is a
            substance, and food objectgs that are
            Kosher will be catgegorized as KosherFoodObjects.

:Thief rdfs:comment A Thief is any Person any sex who 
       has performed Stealing.  This does not mean that the
       person so labeled is a habitual Thief, it only means that
       one can specify some Stealing that was performed by that Person

         Corresponds to a supertype of noun sense 1 of thief in WordNet;
         NOTE that a Thief does not have to be a criminal in COSMO:
           1. 10 thief, stealer - a criminal who takes property belonging
           to someone else with the intention of keeping it or selling it
         .

:NonNaturalThing rdfs:comment The collection of non-natural individuals.  This
                collection is hard to precisely define but, roughly,
                something is an instance of this collection just in case it
                is one of the following: 1 #$Individual acts that are
                intentionally performed by #$IntelligentAgents, or 2
                #$Individuals that in some significant sense  could only
                have been the result  of the intentional activities of
                #$IntelligentAgents or groups thereof.   Positive examples
                in the first category include #$CaesareanSections, negative
                examples include eating.  Positive examples in the second
                category include instances of industrial pollution and tire
                tracks.  Negative examples include human vomit and human
                bare footprints.

:PubliclyHeldOrganization rdfs:comment The collection of all #$CommercialOrganizations
            whose securities or other ownership interests are freely
            tradable among members of the general public, usually on an
            instance of #$FinancialExchange.  In the
            #$UnitedStatesOfAmerica, instances of
            #$PubliclyHeldOrganizations are usually either
            #$LegalCorporations or #$LimitedPartnerships.  Each instance
            of #$PubliclyHeldOrganization in the #$UnitedStatesOfAmerica
            must be registered with the
            #$SecuritiesAndExchangeCommission under the Securities
            Exchange Act of 1934 and is regulated by the #$SecuritiesAndExchangeCommission.

:Velvet rdfs:comment Velvet  is a FlockedFabric with a deep pile.
             Compare Velveteen.
          
              Corresponds to noun sense 1 of velvet in WordNet:
                1. 2 velvet - a silky densely piled fabric with a plain back

:Tough rdfs:comment Tough is an AttributeValue of an Object that
        is not easily broken, or not easily pulled apart. This is
        a physical attribute of SolidObjects, and not
        of people or animals that can withstand hardship.

          Meat that is not tender can be clasified as Tough.

          Corresponds to noun sense 1 of tough in WordNet:
            4. 2 sturdy, tough - substantially made or constructed;
            sturdy steel shelves; sturdy canvas;

:Fertilizer rdfs:comment Any substance organic or inorganic that can
           promote the growth of plants.
           
           This is not necessarily a Nutrient as it can be inorganic.
        
           Corresponds to noun sense 1 of fertilizer in WordNet:
             1. 2 fertilizer, fertiliser, plant food -
                any substance such as manure or a mixture of nitrates used 
                to make soil more fertile

:WaterMoccasin rdfs:comment 
          Corresponds to noun sense 1 of water moccasin in WordNet:
            1. water moccasin, cottonmouth, cottonmouth moccasin, Agkistrodon piscivorus -
              venomous semiaquatic snake of swamps in southern United States

:Bleeding-TheAction rdfs:comment An instance of #$TemporalStuffType and a
            specialization of #$EmittingStuff.  Each instance of
            #$Bleeding-TheAction is a #$BodilyFunctionEvent-Involuntary
            in which #$Blood spills from the body, usually due to a
            wound.  The #$PhysiologicalCondition characterized by
            instances of #$Bleeding-TheAction is #$Bleeding-TheCondition q.v..
            
            Corresponds to verb sense 1 of bleed and noun sense 1 of bleeding 
                in WordNet:
              1. 10 shed blood, bleed, hemorrhage - lose blood from ones body
             WN noun bleeding:
                1. bleeding, hemorrhage, haemorrhage - flow of blood
                     from a ruptured blood vessel

:TheStraitOfHormuz rdfs:comment Note that certain bodies of water, such as Straits and

:Turnip rdfs:comment The Root of a TurnipPlant, from which the TurnipStuff
            is derived.
            
              Corresponds to noun sense 2 of turnip in WordNet:
                2. turnip - root of any of several members of the mustard family
:HydrogenAtom rdfs:comment One atom of Hydrogen; isotopes of specific atomic weight are subtypes.

:TiberRiver rdfs:comment The #$TiberRiver Tivere River a medium-sized
            #$River in Italy that passes through the #$CityOfRomeItaly
            and empties into the #$TyrrhenianSea.

:RelativePoint rdfs:comment A RelativePoint is a Location that is defined by its relation
          to some objects or to some Event; the size of the Point is indefinite, but 
          can be a region.. She walked to a point where she had
           an unobstructed view of the island; They met at a point halfway between
           the two towns; The town is located at the point where the two rivers meet
           
           Corresponds to noun sense 2 of point in WordNet:
             2. 22 point - the precise location of something;
                a spatially limited location; she walked to a point where 
                 she could survey the whole street
             .

:FrictionProcess rdfs:comment An Event in which Frictional forces are
          created.
          
          Cyc: Frictional forces are exerted i.e. a
            #$FrictionProcess occurs so as to inhibit relative motion
            between objects which are in physical contact #$touches
            qv.  If motion is already happening, the force acts in a
            direction opposite to that motion.  If the motion has not
            started, as in the case of static friction, the frictional
            force acts in a direction opposite that of the net applied
            forces.  Examples include air friction, rolling friction,
            mechanical friction.

:Mathematical_Model rdfs:comment Another term for MathematicalRepresentation.  This
          term may be used at soe point as a generalization for all
          math models.

:WaveIntensityMeasure rdfs:comment WaveIntensityMeasure the intensity of some wave phenomenon

         expressible in units when the specific type of wave is
         known.  This is mostly a placeholder as of iteration 195.

:Gate rdfs:comment This sense of gate refers only to the actual physical object
           that swings open and closed, in a portal gateway in a fenced area.
           For the portal, use Gateway.
           
           However, in general use, gate may also refer to the portal or any
             similar opneing to an enclosure, as in RHW sense 2 of gate:
             RHW:  2.  an opening permitting passage through an enclosure.
           
           Corresponds to noun sense 1 of gate in WordNet:
           1. 18 gate - a movable barrier in a fence or wall

:Fair rdfs:comment An attribute value that expresses a judgment
        that the thing evaluated is average or slightly better than average,
        but not Good.
        
         Intensity rankings here are on a goodness scale, with the top
         Good and the bottom Bad

        Corresponds approximately to adjective sense 6 of fair in WordNet:
          6. average, fair, mediocre, middling - lacking exceptional quality 
             or ability; a novel of average merit; only a fair performance of
             the sonata; in fair health; the caliber of the students has gone
             from mediocre to above average; the performance was middling at best
       .

:Potato rdfs:comment A round edible tuber obtained from the
             PotatoPlant.
        
        Corresponds to noun sense 1 of potato in WordNet:
          1. 2 potato, white potato, Irish potato, murphy, spud, tater -
            an edible tuber native to South America; a staple food of Ireland
          .

:BallisticMissile rdfs:comment A collection. Each instance is a #$Missile
            propelled from a #$MissileLauncher that is often mounted on
            a #$Platform-Military. A #$BallisticMissile is generally
            propelled by rockets into the upper atmosphere, and uses the
            gravitational pull to make its high-speed return to the
            surface - either land or water surface - where it
            detonates on contact with the target.
            
            SUMO: A Missile which is guided for the first stage 
            of its flight but then falls to its target for the second stage.

:Poikilotherm rdfs:comment A specialization of #$Animal and an instance of
            #$OrganismClassificationType.  Each instance of
            #$Poikilotherm is a  cold-blooded  animal.  That is, each
            instance is an animal whose body temperature is determined
            mainly by its surrounding environmental temperature.  Cf. #$Homeotherm.
            
            
            Corresponds to noun sense 1 of poikilotherm in WordNet:
              1. poikilotherm, ectotherm - an animal whose body temperature varies 
              with the temperature of its surroundings; any animal except birds and mammals

:Buttocks rdfs:comment The rear fleshey part of the HumanHip, having two
          cheeks.  The part of the body that a perspon sits on.
        
        
        CYC: An instance of #$UniqueAnatomicalPartType and a
            specialization of #$ExternalAnatomicalPart.  Each instance
            of #$Buttocks is a fleshy, bisected protuberance located
            just below the lower back of an animal.
        
        Corresponds to noun sense 1 of buttocks in WordNet:
            1. 1 buttocks, nates, arse, butt, backside, bum, buns, can, 
              fundament, hindquarters, hind end, keister, posterior, prat, rear,
              rear end, rump, stern, seat, tail, tail end, tooshie, tush, 
              bottom, behind, derriere, fanny, ass - the fleshy part of the 
              human body that you sit on; he deserves a good kick in the butt; 
              are you going to sit on your fanny and do nothing?

:Stealing rdfs:comment A specialization of both #$GainingControl and
            #$ActsCommonlyConsideredCriminal.  In each instance of
            #$Stealing, an agent see the collection #$Agent takes
            something belonging to another agent without that
            agents permission and possibly without that
            agents knowledge.  Note that there may be some cases
            in which an agent takes something belonging to another agent
            without that agents explicit permission that would
            nevertheless not be categorized as instances of #$Stealing.
            For instance, a pair of agents may have an informal
            agreement or  understanding  that would cover casual
            borrowing  from one another and thus excuse it from being stealing.
            
            SUMO: Any UnilateralGetting which is not permitted by the 
             origin of the UnilateralGetting.  These cases of UnilateralGetting are 
             distinguished from ones where the destination is the subject of charity or 
             other forms of benefaction.
             
             Corresponds to part of verb sense 1 of steal in WordNet, including
              only the illegal type of stealing not plagiarism, and
              to noun sense 1 of stealing and sense 1 of theftand
              sense 1 of thievery:
               1. 23 steal - take without the owners consent;
                  Someone stole my wallet on the train; This author stole entire 
                  paragraphs from my dissertation
             WN stealing:
               1. 1 larceny, theft, thievery, thieving, stealing - the act of 
                 taking something from someone unlawfully; the thieving is awful 
                 at Kennedy International

:FunctionalAttributeValue rdfs:comment FunctionalAttributeValues are the values taken 
      by a FunctionalAttribute that are OWL classes rather than instances
      of FunctionalAttribute.  The classes are used when a FunctionalAttribute
      value has subtypes that should be reflected in the hierarchy.
      
      The category of LogicalFunction has also been used similarly and 
      more often in COSMO - @ToDo: should these be merged?

:usedTransportationDevice rdfs:comment usedTransportationDevice points from a TransportationEvent
      to some TransportationDevice that was used
      in that Event.  Some composite TransporationEvents may have 
      multiple subevents that are TransporationEvents, and
      each TransportationEvent must use only one TransportationDevice,
      in this particular relation.
      
      In the case where, for example, a container ship 
      carries many containers, and each container is a
      TransportationDevice, the transport via one container
      will be one TransportationEvent if referenced by this relation.
      The composite Event in which multiple containers are shipped on
      one vessel will also be an individual TransportationEvent,
      and the Event of transporting all of those containers can 
      be specified by the use of this relation, pointing to 
      the vessel on which they were transported.
      
      Thus, the placing of an object in a container starts
      one TransportationEvent, using that container.  Placing
      that container in another container, or on a
      TransportationDevice, starts another TransportationEvent.
      Such container-in-container events can be nested indefinitely.

:EnteringaStructure rdfs:comment EnteringaStructure is the Action in which an Agent
         goes from outside to inside of a Structure.  The entering
         can be an entering into a part of a Structure, such as a
         Room, which is also classified as a subtype of Structure in COSMO.
         
          Corresponds to verb sense 1 of enter and verb sense 1 of go into in WordNet;
           1. 89 enter, come in, get into, get in, go into, go in, move into -
             to come or go into; the boat entered an area of shallow marshes

:SportsFacility rdfs:comment SUMO: A specially designated and maintained facility 
         where Sports are played.  Note that this covers sports fields, stadiums, 
         and gymnasiums.

:BadTasting rdfs:comment BadTasting is he opposite of good tasting,
            a general phrase meaning that it is unpleasant to the taste.
            This is not the same as tasteless.
          
          Corresponds to adjective sense 1 of tasty in WordNet:
            1. tasty - - pleasing to the sense of taste

:BusStop rdfs:comment An #$PhysicalObjectType.  Each instance of
            #$BusStop is a #$TransportFacility where one
            #$Bus-RoadVehicle at a time stops to pick up and drop off
            passengers usually at predetermined times.  Note that each
            #$BusStation has many #$BusStops as parts.
            
            SUMO: An area, often, though not necessarily with
            seats or some kind of minimal shelter, where people gather to meet and
            board a bus.  It must border a road.
            
            Corresponds sense 1 of bus stop and to part of noun sense 5 of stop in WordNet:
              1. 1 bus stop - a place on a bus route where buses stop 
                  to discharge and take on passengers
              5. 1 stop - a spot where something halts or pauses; his next stop is Atlanta

:Lion rdfs:comment The collection of large carnivorous feline mammals
            found in Africa.  Does not include mountain lions.
            
            Corresponds to noun sense 1 of lion in WordNet:

               feline of Africa and India having a tawny coat with a shaggy mane in the male

:WindInstrument-Musical rdfs:comment Musical instruments into which one blows air to

:SpinalColumn rdfs:comment The #$SpinalColumn includes every #$Vertebra and
            the spinal discs.   It provides the main support of the
            #$Torso and #$Head-Vertebrate.
            
            SUMO: A flexible column made out of bones called 
            vertebrae. The main function of the SpinalColumn is to protect the 
            spinal cord.
            
            Minimum of 5 vertebrae??
            
            NOTE: in SUMO, this was a subtype of Organ.  In COSMO
            that parent is reserved for soft tissue regions of
            some defined function, with recognizable boundaries..

:CoverableObjectType rdfs:comment Each instance of CoverableObjectType is a type of Object that

:Antigen rdfs:comment The collection of substances that can stimulate
            immune  response. For example, bacteria [#$Bacterium],
            #$Viruses, proteins [#$ProteinMolecule] can serve as #$Antigens.
            
            SUMO: Any BiologicallyActiveSubstance that has the

             Corresponds approximately to noun sense 4 of cause in WordNet:
               1. 11 antigen - any substance as a toxin or enzyme that stimulates

:Share rdfs:comment Each Share is a Part of something that has been divided into
       more than one Part and distributed, allocated, or assigned to some
       agent.  The Share may be something owed or due on the basis of an Agreement
       or Rule someones fair share or may be arbitrarily assigned by the 
       agent doing the distributing.  This is the most general sense of share;
       valuable assets such as money could be part of a more specific
       sense of share.  For share in the sense of share of stock or share
       of some other tradable security, use ShareOfSock.
       
       Corresponds to noun senses 2 and 3 of share and senses 3 and 4 of portion and noun sense 9 of part in WordNet:
         2. 152 share, portion, part, percentage - assets belonging to or due
             to or contributed by an individual person or group; he wanted his share in cash
         3. 117 parcel, portion, share - the allotment of some amount by dividing something;
             death gets more than its share of attention from theologians

:Jainism rdfs:comment Jainism, traditionally known as Jain Dharma, is a spiritual religion
      of Indian origin dating back at least as far as the 9th century BC, 
      but believed by Jains to stretch back many centuries into the very distant past.
      A Jain is a follower of Jinas conquerors, human beings who have
      rediscovered the dharma, become fully liberated and taught the spiritual path 
      for the benefit of beings. Jains follow the teachings of 24 special Jinas
      who are known as Tirthankaras ford-makers, those who have discovered 
      and shown the way to salvation. The 24th and most recent Tirthankar is
      Lord Mahavira who lived from 599 to 527 BCE according to traditional history.
      The 23rd Tirthankar of Jains, Lord Parsvanatha is now recognised as a 
      historical person, who lived during 872 to 772 BC.  Jaina tradition is 
      unanimous in making Rishabha, as the First Tirthankar.[5]

:Fashionable rdf:rest called Event in ISO15926
     COSMO note:  An InstantaneousEvent is a change that occurs instantaneously -
        the change can be said to occur at one point in time: a system has a set
        of attributes that are effective at that point in time, and at any point 
        prior to that, the state may be different in one or more ways. 
        For physical events, this is unrealistic but can be a useful abstraction.
        Certain social or mental events can be said to be instantaneous, such as
        a change in title or position that is scheduled ahead of time.

        In ISO15926 and some situation calculus representations, processes 
        are simply a series of instantaneous changes followed by periods State of no change.
        So this is an important concept for some process representations.

:SportsFacility rdf:type correspondsToDB_Subtable relates some concept
        in the ontology to a portion of a DatabaseTable,
        consisting of some subset of the records rows, and possibly
        also some subset of the columns.  This relation is used when a
        DatabaseTable is used to represent more than one Type in
        an ontology.  The records that represent the Type must be
        recognizable by the value in some field in the whole DatabaseTable.
        For example, a table that represents the characteristics of both people
        and non-human animals might have a special field labeled BorH,
        which distinguishes humans from Beasts non-human animals, and
        for humans, the value in that field would be H, and for
        Beasts the value would be B.  There might be colums that are not used
        for Beast, and likewise columns not used for Human.  Certain fields
        may be used for both Types, but the meaning of the field may
        differ depending on the type.
